<chapter xml:id="chapter-2">
  <title> <m> L^{¥ell} </m> and basic geometry in <m> ¥frac{1}{¥ell}¥mathbb{Z} ¥times ¥mathbb{N}_0</m></title>
    <introduction>
   <!-- ===================== 
    <remark>
    <p>SHAPING THE SUPPORT OF JACOBIAN PAIRS IN</p>
    </remark>
    <note>
    <p>SHAPING THE SUPPORT OF JACOBIAN PAIRS IN.</p>
    </note>
    <p>
    <emph role="bold">SHAPING THE SUPPORT OF JACOBIAN PAIRS IN</emph>
    </p>
    -->
    <p>
    <alert>SHAPING THE SUPPORT OF JACOBIAN PAIRS IN <m> K[x^{ ¥pm ¥frac{1}{¥ell}},y] </m></alert>
    </p> 
    
    
    <p>
    Assume that the Jacobian conjecture is false. As in <xref ref="chapter-1"/>, let <m>B = ¥min¥bigl(¥gcd(¥deg(P),¥deg(Q))¥bigr)</m>, where <m>(P,Q)</m> ranges over all counterexamples. The main result of this chapter is that <m>B ¥ge 16</m>. This lower bound was previously obtained by Heitmann in <cite>H</cite>. To establish this result, we will eliminate six of the seven remaining cases for <m>((a,b),(f_1,f_2))</m> in Table I in <xref ref="defino2-1"/>. Specifically, we will show that in these six cases there do not exist polynomials <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>R</m>, <m>F</m> and a pair <m>(¥rho,¥sigma)</m> as in <xref ref="defino2-1"/>, satisfying
    </p>
    <me>
    ¥operatorname{en}_{¥rho¥sigma}(R) = (a,b) ¥quad ¥text{and} ¥quad ¥operatorname{en}_{¥rho¥sigma}(F) = (f_1,f_2).
    </me>
    <p>
    Consider for example the smallest case (illustrated in <xref ref="defino2-1"/>) with <m>(a,b) = (3,6)</m> and <m>(f_1,f_2) = (2,4)</m>. By item 6 of <xref ref="defino2-1"/>, in this case <m>(¥rho,¥sigma) = (3,-1)</m>. Moreover, <m>¥operatorname{st}_{¥rho¥sigma}(R) = (1,0)</m>, because this is the unique point <m>(c,d)</m> in <m>¥mathbb{N}_0 ¥times ¥mathbb{N}_0</m>, below the main diagonal, satisfying <m>v_{3,-1}(c,d) = v_{3,-1}(3,6)</m>. In order to discard this case we will embed <m>K[x,y]</m> in <m>L^{(3)} := K[x^{¥pm 1/3}, y]</m> and we will use automorphisms of <m>L^{(3)}</m>. By Proposition <xref ref="defino2-1"/>(2) and <xref ref="defino2-1"/>(3), we know that <m>v_{3,-1}(R) > 0</m>, while, by <xref ref="defino2-1"/>(8), we know that <m>[R,F] = R</m>. Thus, <m>R</m> and <m>F</m> fulfill the hypothesis of Proposition <xref ref="defino2-1"/>, with <m>(¥rho,¥sigma) = (3,-1)</m>. Moreover, since <m>z = xy^3</m>, and <xref ref="defino2-1"/>(5) gives <m>¥operatorname{Supp}(F) = ¥{(1,1), (2,4)¥}</m>, it follows necessarily that <m>F ¥sim xy(z-¥lambda)</m> for some <m>¥lambda ¥in K^{¥times}</m>. Hence, by items 2 and 4 of that proposition and the fact that <m>¥operatorname{Supp}(R) ¥subseteq ¥{(1,0), (2,3), (3,6)¥}</m>, we conclude that <m>R ¥sim x(z-¥lambda)^2</m>. Consider the automorphism <m>¥psi</m> of <m>L^{(3)}</m>, defined by
    </p>
    <me>
    ¥psi(x^{1/3}) := x^{1/3} ¥quad ¥text{and} ¥quad ¥psi(y) := y + ¥lambda^{1/3} x^{-1/3}.
    </me>
    <p>
    If we write <m>z^{1/3} := x^{1/3} y ¥in L^{(3)}</m>, then we have <m>¥psi(z^{1/3}) = z^{1/3} + ¥lambda^{1/3}</m>. A direct computation using this and the fact that <m>z - ¥lambda = (z^{1/3})^3 - ¥lambda</m>, shows that
    </p>
    <me>
    ¥psi(F) ¥sim xy¥bigl(z^{1/3} + ¥lambda^{1/3}¥bigr)¥bigl(z^{2/3} + 3z^{1/3}¥lambda^{1/3} + 3¥lambda^{2/3}¥bigr) ¥quad ¥text{and} ¥quad ¥psi(R) ¥sim x z^{2/3}¥bigl(z^{2/3} + 3z^{1/3}¥lambda^{1/3} + 3¥lambda^{2/3}¥bigr)^2.
    </me>
    <p>
    Therefore, by <xref ref="defino2-1"/>, we obtain
    </p>
     <sidebyside widths="70% 30%" valign="middle">

      <p>
        <me>
          ¥operatorname{st}_{3,-1}(¥psi(R)) = (5/3, 2)
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>(see <xref ref="defino2-1"/>)</p>

    </sidebyside>
    <p>
    First we will show that the pair <m>((5/3,2), (¥rho_1,¥sigma_1))</m>, where <m>(¥rho_1,¥sigma_1) := ¥operatorname{Pred}_{¥psi(P)}(3,-1)</m>, is a regular corner (according to <xref ref="defino2-1"/>). But then we will show that this is impossible, discarding the smallest case. For <m>¥ell ¥in ¥mathbb{N}</m>, let <m>L^{(¥ell)} := K[x^{¥pm 1/¥ell}, y]</m> be the commutative <m>K</m>-algebra generated by <m>x^{1/¥ell}</m>, <m>x^{-1/¥ell}</m> and <m>y</m>, subject to the relationship <m>x^{1/¥ell} x^{-1/¥ell} = 1</m>. The general strategy to discard a point <m>(a,b) ¥in L'</m>, where <m>L'</m> is as below of <xref ref="defino2-1"/>, is the following: we will take <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>R</m> and <m>(¥rho,¥sigma)</m> as in <xref ref="defino2-1"/> such that <m>(a,b) =¥operatorname{en}_{¥rho¥sigma}(R)</m>, and we call <m>(¥operatorname{en}_{¥rho¥sigma}(R), (¥rho,¥sigma))</m> a regular corner. Then for some <m>¥ell ¥in ¥mathbb{N}</m>, an automorphism of <m>L^{(¥ell)}</m> will provide us with the next regular corner. We continue with this process and obtain a "complete chain of regular corners" (the precise definitions of these and other notions will be given below). This will allow us to discard the points <m>(a,b)</m> for which there is not such a complete chain. Since the smallest point having a complete chain is <m>(4,12)</m>, this will show that <m>B ¥ge 16</m>. In order to apply this strategy, we will need some results of the first chapter, but generalized for elements in <m>L^{(¥ell)}</m>. Note that <m>K[x,y]</m> is included in <m>K[x^{¥pm 1}, y]</m>, and this algebra is included in <m>L^{(¥ell)}</m>. More generally, <m>L^{(¥ell)}</m> is canonically included in <m>L^{(h)}</m> whenever <m>¥ell ¥mid h</m>. The elements of <m>K[x,y]</m> have their support in <m>¥mathbb{N}_0 ¥times ¥mathbb{N}_0</m>, whereas the elements of <m>L^{(¥ell)}</m> have their support in <m>¥frac{1}{¥ell} ¥mathbb{Z} ¥times ¥mathbb{N}_0</m>.
    </p> 
  </introduction>
